    <text>
        <body>
            <p>To the President and members of the</p>
            <p><addressee>K. K. M. I.</addressee> of <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Gentlemen.</p>
            <p>It is as you all know, a laudable feeling, to be in<lb/> possession of the good
                opinion of our fellow-beings; how<lb/> much more must this be the case with a
                person<lb/> who has held a public trust, to be assured that he<lb/> has acted so as
                to elicit the approbation of his<lb/> constituents. It has now happened, that
                up<lb/> to this day I have not been honoured with a certi<lb/>ficate from your
                honourable body such as I think<lb/> my long public services merit; I would
                therefore<lb/> be indebted to you to obtain at the earliest pos<lb/>sible moment
                such an expression of your kind<lb/> opinion as I could exhibit to all the world
                as<lb/> the evidence that my long public services as the<lb/> minister of your
                congregation have met with your<lb/> approbation.</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">Respe S.</p>
            <p rend="indent(12)">
                <persName role="author">Isaac Leeser</persName>
            </p>
            <p><placeName>Phila.</placeName>
                <date>March 29<hi rend="sup">th</hi>. 5617</date>. </p>
        </body>
    </text>
